AGI - The life of the Slovak Prime Minister Robert Fico is not in danger <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-15/slovacchia-media-spari-su-premier-fico-arrestato-aggressore-26395030/"> after the attack. </a> This is the opinion expressed by the deputypremier and minister of the environment, Tomas Taraba in an interview with the Bbc. "I think he'll eventually survive," Taraba said. "At the moment, he's not in danger of life." The vicepremier confirmed that the surgery to which the premier was subjected shortly after the attack went well.&nbsp;
<h2 The offended Fico bomber risks life-threatening
The man who shot the Slovak prime minister, the populist Robert Fico, was charged with "tentato murder premeditated for revenge", a felony that could lead a 25-year sentence to life imprisonment.<br> The man, the 71-year-old Juraj Cintula, is currently held in the premises of a special unit of criminal police in the city of Nitra.<br> According to journalistic sources, Cintula told police officers to be proud of what he did.

